<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Strategy Tips</h2>

<div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Extend adjectives on the board:</span> If QUICK, SHARP, or BOLD is already played, adding -LY creates a bingo-length word and scores all letters plus premium squares the extension crosses. This is one of the easiest extensions in the game.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Y on premium squares:</span> Y is worth 4 points — more than most players realize. Position -LY endings so the Y lands on a double or triple letter score. On DLS, Y alone contributes 8 points; on TLS, 12 points.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Non-adverb -LY words:</span> Remember standalone words like SUPPLY, JELLY, BULLY, and RALLY. These aren't adjective+LY constructions, so opponents may not think to challenge them. They're also shorter and fit tight boards.</p>
  </div>
</div>

